Binary-Search-Tree.content:
Definition:
A Binary Tree which follows the rule that LEFT \le NODE &lt; RIGHT.

Notes:
This is quite similar to Quicksort, where the node value acts like the pivot.
However, it’s even easier!
Binary Tree Search
function search(curr: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt; | null, needle: number): boolean {
	if (!curr) {
		return false;
	}
	if (curr.val === needle) {
		return true;
	}

	// recursion
	if (needle &lt; curr.val) {
		return search(curr.left, needle);
	}
	return search(curr.right, needle);
}

export default function dfs(head: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt;, needle: number): boolean {
	return serach(head, needle);
}
Insertion
Note this is very naive because we aren’t balancing the tree.
insert(node, v):
	// note: we need a check for if the tree is empty.
	if node.val &lt; v:
		insert(node.right, v);
	else if node.val &gt;= v:
		insert(node.left, v);
Deletion
Cases

If the node is a leaf, then we can just delete it.
If the node has one child: we can remove the middle node. parent.child = cur.child
If the node has two children:

Let’s find the Max-Min, i.e., largest value in the left subtree (or Min-Max)
This is guaranteed to fit the Binary Tree principle.
It also has to be a leaf node (otherwise, it can’t be the largest small or smallest large, as it would have a left or right).
Replace the root node with this value.
Ideally, you pick this so that it balances the tree as best as possible.



