Definition:
Methods of going through a tree using Recursion


Notes:
Pre-Order Traversal:

Visit the node
Visit the left
Visit the right

This is DFS using Recursion and the Stack.
// add node values to array called path
// pre-order traversal
function walk(
	curr: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt; | null,
	path: number[]
): number[] {
	// base case
	if (!curr) {
		return path;
	}

	// pre
	path.push(curr.value);

	// recurse
	walk(curr.left, path);
	walk(curr.right, path);

	// post
	return path;
}
In-Order Traversal:

Visit the left
Visit the node
Visit the right

This is DFS using Recursion and the Stack.
// add node values to array called path
// pre-order traversal
function walk(
	curr: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt; | null,
	path: number[]
): number[] {
	// base case
	if (!curr) {
		return path;
	}

	// pre

	// recurse
	walk(curr.left, path);
	path.push(curr.value);
	walk(curr.right, path);

	// post
	return path;
}
Post-Order Traversal:

Visit the left
Visit the right
Visit the node

This is DFS using Recursion and the Stack.

Used for freeing memory.

// add node values to array called path
// pre-order traversal
function walk(
	curr: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt; | null,
	path: number[]
): number[] {
	// base case
	if (!curr) {
		return path;
	}

	// pre

	// recurse
	walk(curr.left, path);
	walk(curr.right, path);

	// post
	path.push(curr.value);
	return path;
}
Tree Level Traversal

While you have a queue:

Get the next node from the queue
Add the children to the queue



This is BFS using a Queue. See also Leetcode 102 Binary Tree Level Order.
NOTE: This does NOT preserve tree structure (e.g., see Leetcode 100 Same Binary Tree)
export default function bfs(head: BinaryNode&lt;number&gt;, needle: number): boolean {
	const q: (BinaryNode&lt;number&gt; | null)[] = [head]; // we should use a real LL-based queue to avoid O(N) shift

	while (q.length) {
		const curr = q.shift() as BinaryNode&lt;number&gt;;  // O(N) arr copy
		if (!curr) {
			continue;
		}

		// search
		if (curr.value === needle) {
			return true;  // marginally better to not return from loop
		}

		// add to queue
		// none case is handled up front
		q.push(curr.left);
		q.push(curr.right);
	}

	return false;
}
Big O

We must visit each node in the whole tree.
As the tree grows by 1 node, we need to visit an additional node.
